The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, February 12, 2004 				 Zee to shop for $100m overseas
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Mumbai, Feb. 11: The board of Zee Telefilms has proposed raising $100 million through convertible bonds that could be listed on an international exchange.																								Essentially an external commercial borrowing, the bonds will be converted into shares, the company told bourses today. Though there was no word on which overseas exchange has been chosen for a possible listing, analysts say it will one of those in Europe.																								The funds will be used for investments in equipment upgrade and other purposes. Industry watchers say it could also help restructure the old debt pile with early repayments and to prune interest costs. Shareholders will take a call on March 9.																								The Zee share closed at Rs 151.15 on the Bombay Stock Exchange, up Rs 3.10 or 2.1 per cent from Rs 148.05 on Tuesday.																								The move puts Zee among the horde of firms queuing up to raise foreign funds after Moodys raised Indias foreign currency rating to Ba3 from Ba1. 
